{{Infobox award | name = Hamilton King Award | alt = | caption = | description = Excellence in illustration | presenter = [[Society of Illustrators]] | country = United States | year = 1965 | website = }}
The '''Hamilton King Award''' is an annual award, presented to one individual, for excellence in illustration by the [[Society of Illustrators]].
== History ==
The Hamilton King Award was established in 1965 by Mrs. Hamilton King in memory of her husband through a bequest and is presented annually for the best illustration in the annual exhibition executed by a member of the [[Society of Illustrators]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Society of Illustrators | url=http://www.societyillustrators.org/HamiltonKing.aspx?id=140 | accessdate=2013-05-26}}</ref>
Hamilton King (1871–1941)<ref>[http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/benz/9780199773787.article.B00098749?rskey=dp4IvD&result=9 Benezit Dictionary of Artists]</ref> was a prominent illustrator who worked in the late 1800s and early 1900s.<ref>[http://www.americanartarchives.com/king,h.htm americanartarchives]</ref> King illustrated the "[[Coca-Cola]] girls" for calendars from 1910 to 1913. The Coca-Cola calendar work was considered significant because the artist's signature appeared in all printed matter for Coca-Cola, including serving trays.<ref>{{cite web | title=Famous Artists Who Have Worked With Coca-Cola | url=http://www.coca-colacompany.com/stories/coke-lore-commissioned-artists | date=2012-01-01}}</ref>
King became well known for his "Hamilton King Girls", significantly working on behalf of [http://www.metmuseum.org/en/collections/search-the-collections?&what=Color+lithographs&who=Turkish+Trophies+Cigarettes&pg=1 Turkish Trophies Cigarettes]. A majority of this collection is held by [[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Metropolitan Museum of Art | url=http://www.metmuseum.org/collections/search-the-collections?ft=*&amp;who=Hamilton+King | accessdate=2013-05-26}}</ref> Additional collections of the artist are held by the [[Smithsonian Institution]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Smithsonian Institution | url=http://collections.si.edu/search/results.htm?q=Hamilton%20King&sType=%22phrase%22 | accessdate=2013-05-26}}</ref>
